INSERT INTO compass_notes (contract_id, meeting_id, note_type, title, content_raw, note_date, status, action_items, is_auto_generated)
SELECT
  new_meeting.contract_id,
  new_meeting.meeting_id,
  'meeting',
  'Meeting Notes: Rugged Robotics <> MiD Bi-Weekly',
  '## **Data Sourcing and AI Filtering for Prospect Lists**

The team refined the prospect list by combining AI-driven filters with domain and job title data to improve targeting accuracy.

- **The master company list consists of 283 rows**, split between hyperscaler and non-hyperscaler companies, with **five hyperscalers including Oracle recently added** (02:16)
    - Hyperscaler prospects are filtered by domain, job titles, seniority, and profile keywords to focus on likely candidates
    - Tristan explained they use OpenAI via CLAY to generate a "prospect qualify" score based on LinkedIn profile summaries, enabling a smarter filter than traditional keyword matching
    - A sample AI test on 10 profiles showed about **30% of prospects meet criteria**, suggesting around **1,500 qualified prospects** when applied to the full database
    - AI helps identify infrastructure-related roles but struggles to perfectly separate software vs. construction roles, requiring ongoing prompt refinement

- **Non-hyperscaler list filtering reduced 3,000 companies to about 500 prospects without AI**, capturing more construction-specific titles but fewer varied roles (12:59)
    - Rob suggested differentiating project manager titles by company type, allowing inclusion of "project manager" for general contractors but not hyperscalers
    - Location filtering to exclude prospects outside the US was planned to improve relevance
    - The team agreed to exclude Amazon and review key client domains like Turner to avoid duplicates or irrelevant targets
    - Tristan will provide Rob CSV exports for validation and job title lists to refine filters (15:39)

- **Rob requested exploring a reverse LinkedIn API approach** to retrieve all job titles at specific companies for better title coverage and to identify possible filtering gaps (16:01)
    - Tristan to attempt creating a company table with job titles for a few key companies like Turner and Vanderla to give Rob a clear view (17:41)
    - Rob plans to analyze this data to address AI’s limitations and uncover missing roles (16:19)

## **Email Outreach Strategy and Content Adjustments**

Email messaging was reviewed with a focus on improving engagement and avoiding spam filters.

- **The first email currently avoids hyperlinks to reduce spam risk but may include domain names in parentheses**, as suggested by Tristan (20:15)
    - Rob proposed switching case studies from PDFs to website-based success stories, making links more relevant and clickable (20:47)
    - A hyperlink could be introduced later in the sequence (emails 4 or 5) to nurture interest before asking for clicks (21:21)
    - Adding a line like "Interested in learning more?" to the first email was agreed to increase response rates (21:50)

## **Website Staging Environment and Content Management**

Rob is gaining control over the WordPress site but needs guidance on managing page hierarchy and template structures.

- **Rob is comfortable editing text and photos but cautious about deleting parent pages that remove child pages**, which risks losing important content (23:10)
    - Tristan recommended recording a Loom video to document specific deletion questions for the development team to assist (24:08)
    - Demir, who built the staging environment and new pages, remains the best contact for complex WordPress questions (22:48)
    - Tristan explained the site uses advanced custom fields (ACF) and PHP template files, making it difficult to visualize page assembly without developer support (25:40)
    - Rob is learning the relationship between templates, layouts, and flexible content fields but finds it challenging to identify where front-end views correspond to backend templates (28:00)
    - Tristan showed the theme file editor and explained the PHP snippets linked to layout components, highlighting the complexity for non-developers (27:56)
    - Rob plans to mostly work within existing frameworks and carefully remove sections, knowing he can restore anything if needed (31:29)

## **Next Steps and Deliverables**

Clear follow-up tasks and information exchange were planned to refine prospect data and support website management.

- Tristan will send Rob the current prospect lists, including company and job title tables, by the end of the day for review and validation (31:58)
- Tristan will build location filters and exclude certain domains, per Rob’s input, to improve list quality (14:44)
- Rob will analyze job title exports and explore LinkedIn API data to identify gaps and adjust filters accordingly (16:01)
- Rob will prepare specific questions and video walkthroughs regarding WordPress page deletions and template concerns for Demir or Tristan’s team to address (24:08)
- Tristan offered to provide hands-on support for complex website updates beyond Rob’s scope (24:43)',
  '2025-12-10 15:00:00+00',
  'published',
  '[{"text":"Apply location-based filters to company and contact database, excluding non-US and specific clients (e.g., Amazon) (14:44)","completed":false},{"text":"Export comprehensive job title lists from selected companies’ data for Rob''s review and refinement (19:51)","completed":false},{"text":"Send CSV exports of filtered prospect lists to Rob for validation (15:39)","completed":false},{"text":"Coordinate with Demir on any technical website questions forwarded from Rob (24:43)","completed":false},{"text":"Validate AI-filtered prospect CSVs and provide feedback on relevancy (15:39)","completed":false},{"text":"Prepare Loom video or detailed questions on WordPress page deletion and site management for technical support (24:21)","completed":false},{"text":"Test manual website edits in staging, primarily text and images, while avoiding risky deletions without guidance (23:45)","completed":false},{"text":"Provide sample companies for generating comprehensive job title datasets and review discrepancies (17:41)","completed":false}]'::jsonb,
  true
FROM new_meeting;

